	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Which game? Are you trying to edit 8x16 pixel sprites? Otherwise, how do you expect a generic tile editor to know which order the game program uses the tiles in? It appears you want a tile editor that runs within an emulator, and this is about the <em>only</em> reason I'd use nesticle nowadays.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Memblers</b> [ Wed Dec 08, 2004 11:09 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />YY-CHR is a good editor, it has options to reorganize the tiles in various modes too, which works with graphics for some games.
<br />
<br />If you want to edit the actual screen, you'll need to modify the tilemap (nametable) data.  Since they all use different formats for it, usually only level editors for specific games can do it (easily).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


